INTRODUCTION¶

This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area. I'll be exploring this dataset using visualisations to gain insights from the data.

Let's change the columns to appropriate datatypes.¶
In [5]:
# Changing the start and end times from string to datetime format
original_df.start_time = pd.to_datetime(original_df.start_time)
original_df.end_time = pd.to_datetime(original_df.end_time)

original_df.member_birth_year = pd.to_datetime(original_df.member_birth_year, format = '%Y')
Let's Change The Id columns from floats/int to Objects¶
In [6]:
original_df['start_station_id'] = original_df['start_station_id'].astype(str)
original_df['end_station_id'] = original_df['end_station_id'].astype(str)
original_df['bike_id'] = original_df['bike_id'].astype(str)
Let's Change The Member's gender and user type columns to Categorical Datatypes.¶
In [7]:
original_df.member_gender = original_df.member_gender.astype('category')
original_df.user_type = original_df.user_type.astype('category')

Creating New Columns for Month, Day and Hour From the Start_time column¶

In [9]:
# Creating the months column
original_df['start_month']= original_df['start_time'].dt.month_name()

# Creating day name Column
weekdays = ['Monday','Tuesday', 'Wednesday', 'Thursday', 'Friday', 'Saturday', 'Sunday']
original_df['start_day'] = pd.Categorical(original_df.start_time.dt.strftime('%A'), categories=weekdays, ordered=True)

# Creating the Hour column in 12 Hour Format
am_pm = ['12 AM', '01 AM', '02 AM', '03 AM', '04 AM', '05 AM', '06 AM', '07 AM', '08 AM', '09 AM', '10 AM', '11 AM', '12 PM', '01 PM', '02 PM', '03 PM', '04 PM', '05 PM', '06 PM', '07 PM', '08 PM', '09 PM', '10 PM', '11 PM']
original_df['start_hour'] = pd.Categorical(original_df.start_time.dt.strftime('%I %p'), categories=am_pm, ordered=True)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The Ford GoBike System data consists of 183412 rows with a total of 16 columns. In other words, there are 183412 records and 16 variables. By using 'df.info' we can see the number of rows and columns, as well as the datatypes in the dataset. I noticed the data only covers report for just the month of febuary 2019 mostly, with some end times stretching to march.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main features of interest in this dataset is duration_sec, start_time.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

To help us gain much understanding about the rides features such as user type, member birth year and gender I created a few new columns "month", "Day", "hour" by extracting it from 'Start_time' for the purpose of further analysis.

In [15]:
## Ploting the Chart Using Logarithmic Scale
bin10 =  10 ** np.arange(1.7, 5+0.1,0.1) 
ticks = [0.1, 0.3, 1, 3, 10, 30, 100, 300, 1000, 3000, 10000, 30000, 100000]
labels = ['{}'.format(v) for v in ticks]
plt.hist(data=df, x = 'duration_sec', bins = bin10)
plt.xscale('log')
plt.xticks(ticks, labels)
plt.xlim(30,80000);

Now we can see in more details the distribution of the duration time. we observed that the log plot is symentrical and unimodal, and most of the distribution of the duration falls somewhere within 60 to 10,000 seconds, but we can see some outliers past 10,000 upto 30,000 and beyond. Because this plot is symentrical and unimodal, the mean is located at the centre of the distribution... Looking a the plot, the mean is somewhere around 700 secs.

In [17]:
# Creating Function to plot Seaborn's Count plot 
def sns_countplot(x_col, order_col):
    countplot = sns.countplot(x= x_col, data=df, order = df[order_col].value_counts().index)
    return countplot
In [18]:
# Creating a function to plot matplotlib Pie Charts
def plt_pie(col_name):
    v_count = df[col_name].value_counts()
    piechart = plt.pie(v_count, labels = v_count.index, startangle = 90, autopct='%1.2f%%')
    return piechart
In [19]:

At 6am, we start to notice more people have started their trip, the growth in number increases rapidly to a peak at 8am, then declines at 9am, stays fairly stable throughout the afternoon, and during the evening around 4pm, we start to obeserve inscrease in the number of rides, that rapidly reaches the peak of the day at 5pm, then consistently declines towards the end of the day at night.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

As earlier stated my main features are the duration and start time. I noticed there were a few outliers in the histogram of the duration which means that a few persons finished thier rides in a relatively very long time. For tarnsformation, I had to plot the histogram in logarithmic scale to further inspect the distribution.

For the start time (during the day), as expected I observed lower number of rides during the night time and very early hours in the morning, we observed the first peak during 8am, this could be due to the the assumption that most people go to school,work etc around 8am, and we also notice the second and highest peak during 5pm, could be the closing time of most institutions or work places, then again these are merely speculations.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

I noticed some unusual distribution in the member_birth_year variable. The oldest member there is about 141 years old, which I very much doubt that someone that old would be able to ride a bike. Some members were over 100 years old which is very unlikey possible as only about 5% of the population or less is 80+ years according to https://censusreporter.org/profiles/16000US0667000-san-francisco-ca/ and https://www.populationu.com/cities/san-francisco-populationand, the average age is about 38. Asides from that, the birth_year distribution is right skewed implying that there are mostly younger people than older people.

I changed a couple of columns data types to more appropriate datatypes for my analysis. These include changing the start_time,end_time and member_birth_year columns to datetime format, then changing the bike_id, start_station and end_station to strings, then changing member_gender and user type to categorical datatypes.

I also created three additional columns by extracting from the start_time column. These includes, the month, the day of the week and the time of the day

BIVARIATE¶

In [31]:
# Creating a function to plot a bivariate bar chart, where the first variable is whichever column we choose and the second variable in the mean duration_sec
def avg_dur_based_on(col_name):
    bi_barplot = df.groupby(col_name)['duration_sec'].mean().plot.bar()
    return bi_barplot

Does the start time influence the mean duration of rides?¶

In [36]:
# Creating function to plot bivariate line chart, first variable will be whichever column we choose and the second is the  mean of duration_sec column
def avg_dur_lineplot(col_name):
    time = df.groupby(col_name)['duration_sec'].mean()
    line_plot = sns.lineplot(data=time)
    return line_plot
In [37]:
plt.figure(figsize=(20,7))

plt.title('Average Trip Duration Based on Start Time During The Day',  fontsize=20)
plt.xlabel('Time of The Day', fontsize=14);
plt.ylabel('Duration In Seconds',  fontsize=14);

We can see that in contrast to the number of rides during the day, those who started biking in the early part of the day from 2am to 3am had the highest trip duration probably people who do it for hardcore excercise or training, then the avgerage duration declines drastically from 4am till 6am, then the average duration starts to increase from 7am gradually till 11am and and stay staggering throughout the afternoon, and starts declining by 4pm towards the evening.

Which days are riders most active based on trip duration?¶

In [38]:

Despite the results from the 'Number of Trips During The Week' chart, where most of the rides were carried out during the week, here we can see that trip duration were longer on the weekends and significantly lower on the week days. This makes sense to me, as I imagine a lot of trips during the week are for offical movements such as school, work, etc hence people might be in a hurry to reach their destinations, however during the weekends, I imagine people ride for recreation, excercise, training etc, so they may not be in a rush to get to their distination.

They are mostly active from 8am to 6pm, this makes me speculate that most of the customers maybe students,workers etc as they there are more rides seen during convention "official working hours"... This is marely a speculation, but I found it interesting.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

I'd like to point out that from the 'Average Trip Duration Based on User Type' chart we observed that Customers significantly spend time biking than subscribers generally. Regardless of this, upon deeper analyses we discovered that there were more Subscriber than customer in each gender class and the customers had a lower average duration of rides in comparison to the subscribers across all the gender class. This could imply that the customers travel shorter distances. But due to the limitations in this dataset, these are merely speculations. It's quite an interesting twist.

Conclusions¶

In conclusion, this analyses has been able to show the distributions and frequencies of variables in the dataset. It also showed the splits over genders, start time during the day and during the week, user type as well as bike share options and how these affected the duration of the rides.

During the course of this project, we've been able to answer several question brained stormed earlier. In summary these are my findings...

  • Bike Sharing and Duration

    Despite the disparity in the Number of users that do not share which is larger, and the bikers that shared, the average duration between both groups are very close. Based on this I speculate that bike sharing doesn't strongly influence trip durations.

  • Average Duration Based on User Type

    Generally, Customers significantly spend time biking than subscribers generally. Regardless of this, upon deeper analyses we discovered that there were more Subscriber than customer in each gender class and the customers had a lower average duration of rides in comparison to the subscribers across all the gender class.

  • Hours of use Based on User Type

    I observed that Subscriber travel throughout the day from morning till night, however the customers tend to travel more during the day especially during work hours... This has lead me to speculate that most of the customers aren't hardcore bikers, probably just bike for regular commute. But with the the limited data, we cannot investigate further.

  • Hours of use Based on Gender

    I observed that the males travel throughout the day from morning till night, however the females and the 'other' gender tend to travel more just before and after sunrise.
